First, we compute the two measures step by step.

1. Quick Ratio

Quick assets include cash and equivalents (Cash on Hand, Bank Deposits), Interest Receivable, and Accounts Receivable. Note that inventory is excluded. Using the balance sheet end-of-period numbers:

• Cash on Hand: 6,057,264.53  
• Bank Deposits: 1,020,005.47  
• Interest Receivable: 14,887.89  
• Accounts Receivable: 14,921,566.06  

Sum of quick assets = 6,057,264.53 + 1,020,005.47 + 14,887.89 + 14,921,566.06 = 22,013,723.95

Current liabilities (end) = 8,028,630.43

Thus, Quick Ratio = Quick Assets / Current Liabilities
  = 22,013,723.95 / 8,028,630.43
  ≈ 2.74

2. Net Profit Margin

Net Profit Margin is calculated as Net Profit divided by Total Revenue.
From the income statement:
• Net Profit = 3,744,117.89  
• Total Revenue = 28,572,608.70  

Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100%
  = (3,744,117.89 / 28,572,608.70) × 100%
  ≈ 0.1311 × 100%
  ≈ 13.11%

Thus, the answer is:

  "solution": {"Quick Ratio": "2.74", "Net Profit Margin": "13.11%"}
